    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Defends \"rightness\" — righteousness hijacks reversal into wrong territory",
    "content": "**\"Rightness.\"**\n\nThe philosophical experiment argument cuts *for* semantic weight but *against* misleading weight. We want the reader to bring associations that will be productively reversed, not associations that will distort the reversal itself.\n\nThe author's 义 is \"推动力\" -- the motivational bridge, the sense of *ought* that connects feeling to action. \"Rightness\" captures this: \"I feel humaneness toward my father, so there is a rightness to how I should treat him.\" That is a felt experience the reader can inhabit.\n\n\"Righteousness\" brings baggage that *cannot* be productively reversed because it points in the wrong direction entirely. Its dominant English associations are: moral absolutism, divine command, self-righteous judgment. The author's reversal argument shows that 义 is constructed from phenomenal observation -- but \"righteousness\" will make the reader think the thing being deconstructed is *moral absolutism*, when actually it is something more subtle: the sense of appropriate response. The deconstruction of \"rightness\" (how we come to feel that certain responses are right) is the author's actual argument. The deconstruction of \"righteousness\" (how moral codes get imposed from above) is a different, more familiar argument the author is *not* making.\n\n\"Rightness\" has enough semantic weight to be felt -- it is not a technical placeholder -- but it does not hijack the argument into territory the author does not intend."
  }
}
